ell as developments in the field and revisions of the Gothic traditionConstitutes the first thematic compendium to this area with a transmedia (literature, film and television) and transnational approachCovers a plurality of texts, from novels such as Stephenie Meyer’s Twilight (2005), Helen Oyeyemi’s White Is for Witching (2009), Justin Cronin’s The Passage (2010) and M.R. Carey’s The Girl with All the Gifts (2014), to films such as Kairo (2001), Juan of the Dead (2012) and The Darkside (2013), to series such as Dante’s Cove (2005–7), Hemlock Grove (2013–15), Penny Dreadful (2014–16), Black Mirror (2011–) and even the Slenderman mythosThis resource in contemporary Gothic literature, film and television takes a thematic approach, providing insights into the many forms the Gothic has taken in the twenty-first century. The 20 newly commissioned chapters cover emerging and expanding research areas, such as digital technologies, queer identity, the New Weird and postfeminism. They also discuss contemporary Gothic monsters – including zombies, vampires and werewolves – and highlight Ethnogothic forms such as Asian and Black Diasporic Gothic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aGoth culture (Subculture) 0aGoth culture (Subculture)y21st century. 0aGoth culture (Subculture). 0aGothic fiction (Literary genre)y21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aGothic revival (Literature) 0aGothic revival (Literature). 0aHorror filmsxHistory and criticism. 0aHorror television programsxHistory and criticism. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh1 aAldana Reyes, Xavier, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aAlthans, Katrin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAncuta, Katarzyna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators